The music of House of Rabbits blends dark, theatrical, narrative songwriting and lyrics with a variety of musical styles ranging from raucous mock-operatic circus punk to hushed, atmospheric, bossa nova cocktail jazz. Preferring abrupt tonal changes to a catchy, contrived chorus hook, the members of HoR focus on creating challenging, interesting, impossible to categorize music that constantly defies genre while still remaining accessible with their infectiously dance-worthy rhythms.

HoR formed in 2014 after their previous avant-art-metal project FEASTofFETUS went through a major line-up change and the current members (Cron, Caffell, Kovari, Malcolm) found themselves collaborating on material which began to take the band in a new direction. They opted for a different kind of heavy sound; trading the distorted metal guitar chugging for something more akin to a piano falling down stairs.

House of Rabbits self-recorded and self-released their first 4-song live demo entitled “Demo 2014” over the course of 2 days in July of 2014. The concept of these 4 tracks sparked the idea for Cron to write an accompanying theater piece to coincide with the music. After the script was picked up by an award-winning producer/director team, Eloy Palacios joined as the band’s bassist and House of Rabbits began writing the remaining 10 songs for their vaudeville rock-musical masquerade entitled House of Rabbits’ Charivari in Voyeurville. The rock-musical premiered at the 2015 Hollywood Fringe Festival, sold out all six 99-seat performances to standing room only capacity, garnished much critical praise from LA Weekly and won several nominations and awards (The Encore Producer’s Award, theTVolution.com Platinum Medal/Best of Fringe) including an additional 3-day run of the show.

House of Rabbits are currently at work recording their debut, 14-track, full-length record with composer/guitarist/engineer Jason Schimmel (Secret Chiefs 3, John Zorn). This album will be comprised of tracks from the demo as well as songs from the Charivari production and is entitled “Songs of Charivari”. HoR have raised $5,713 in order to fund their new record thanks to a successful Kickstarter campaign and plans to self-release this record on Cron’s own label, Grotesque Requords, in time for a Northwest tour in spring of
